SELECT m.id, 'Personal Cell Phone Use', 'personal-cell-phone-use', '<h2>Personal Cell Phone Use</h2>
<p>When it comes to our attendance policy at Innovative Air Technologies, we have specific guidelines regarding personal cell phone use during work hours. It is important to note that personal phone use is prohibited in the factory while employees are on duty. This policy is in place to ensure that our employees remain focused on their tasks and maintain a safe working environment.</p>
<p>However, we understand the importance of staying connected, which is why employees are allowed to use their personal devices during designated breaks or lunch periods. This provides an opportunity for individuals to check their phones, make personal calls, or respond to messages without interfering with their work responsibilities.</p>
<p>For company-related tasks that require the use of a device or computer, Innovative Air Technologies will provide the necessary equipment. This ensures that employees have access to the tools they need to effectively perform their job duties without relying on personal devices.</p>
<p>In the event of an emergency during office hours, employees can rest assured that their family and friends can reach them by contacting the main office number at <strong>770-788-6744</strong>. This allows for efficient communication in urgent situations while maintaining a professional and organized approach to handling personal matters during work hours.</p>
<h3>Using your personal cell phone/device for IAT business is allowed:</h3>
<ul>
<li>During breaks or at lunch hour</li>
<li>To briefly check important IAT messages</li>
<li>To conduct company business (Supervisor Approval Required)</li>
<li>To make business calls</li>
</ul>
<h3>The following rules apply at all times for both company-issued and personal phones:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Company-issued phones are to be used for business purposes only.</li>
<li>The use of a phone for any reason while driving a company vehicle is prohibited</li>
<li>The download or upload of inappropriate, illegal, or obscene material through a corporate internet connection is prohibited</li>
<li>The use of a cell phone''s camera or microphone to record confidential information is strictly prohibited</li>
<li>Surfing the internet, texting, and talking on the phone should be restricted to IAT business only</li>
<li>Playing games on the cell phone during working hours is prohibited.</li>
</ul>', 31, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Leave Policy Overview', 'leave-policy-overview', '<h2>Leave Policy Overview</h2>
<blockquote><p><strong>Leave Policies are our way of giving you a high-five for managing work and life without missing a beat.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Our Leave Policies lay out all the options for taking a break, whether you need a sick day, some vacation time, or you''re welcoming a new family member.</p>
<p>Having these rules in black and white allows us to maintain a positive work environment. It means everyone knows where they stand, making it easier to plan who''s doing what and when.</p>
<p>Plus, it keeps things fair and square, so there''s no drama about who gets time off. In short, clear leave policies are all about keeping everyone happy and making sure the show goes on smoothly.</p>', 32, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Annual Time', 'annual-time', '<h2>Annual Time</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Vacation photo — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<blockquote><p><em>We know you want time off... Here''s how you get it...</em></p></blockquote>
<p>If you''re with us full-time and on a permanent basis, you get to rack up some hours every month for Annual Leave. You can use these hours to take some paid time off. Just a heads up, though, this Annual Leave Time policy is only for the full-timers, not for our temporary role friends.</p>
<h3>Employees will start to earn on the anniversary of hire date:</h3>
<ul>
<li>&lt;1 year: 5 hrs/month = 60 hrs per year</li>
<li>1–4 years: 6.67 hrs/month = 80 hrs per year</li>
<li>5–9 years: 10 hrs/month = 120 hrs per year</li>
<li>10+ years: 13.34 hrs/month = 160 hrs per year</li>
</ul>
<h3>Just a heads up on how we''re handling vacations and time off:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Stacking vacations back-to-back is a no-go, let''s keep it spaced out.</li>
<li>We can''t have two folks from the same area off at the same time or taking consecutive weeks off. But hey, if you chat with your manager, there might be some wiggle room. Remember that Open Door Policy we talked about earlier?</li>
<li>Ran out of vacation time? No worries, you can dip into the negatives up to 40 hours. Just a heads up, if you decide to part ways with us and you''re in the red, we''ll need to settle that with your last paycheck.</li>
<li>Didn''t use all your hours? They''ll roll over to next year, up to 240 hours.</li>
<li>If you end up with more than 240 hours at the end of the year, we''ll pay out the extra.</li>
<li>When you want to use your Annual Time, just fill out the right <strong>Annual Time Request Form</strong> and get it to your supervisor for approval.</li>
<li>Planning a big getaway? Just make sure to get your request in at least 2 weeks ahead if it''s 30+ hours.</li>
<li>Need a shorter break? Those under 30 hours are up to your manager, so have a chat with them.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p><strong>Let''s all try to make this work smoothly. Thanks, team!</strong></p></blockquote>
<h3>Annual Time may be requested for the following reasons:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Personal Time Off</li>
<li>Vacation Time</li>
<li>Leave Early (a need arises)</li>
</ol>', 33, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Annual Time Form', 'annual-time-form', '<h2>Annual Time Form</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>Taking some time off is pretty key at any workplace, right?</em></p></blockquote>
<p>At Innovative Air Technologies, we''ve got this annual time off request form that everyone needs to fill out when they want to take a break. It''s our way of keeping everything organized and making sure everyone''s schedules mesh well together.</p>
<p>If you''re scratching your head wondering how to tackle that form, don''t sweat it! Check out the super handy video right below that walks you through the whole process. It''s like having a buddy show you the ropes, making sure you get everything down pat so your time off request slides through without a hitch.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Annual Time Request Form video tutorial — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Here''s the form link — be sure to bookmark it for easy access!</p>
<p><a href="https://www.dehumidifiers.com/annual-time-request">Annual Time Request Form | Dehumidifiers.com</a></p>
<blockquote><p>Employees may not take a day off that falls after or before a holiday. Employees may not take a day off to "make" 40 hrs. on a time card for the week.</p></blockquote>', 34, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Overtime', 'overtime', '<h2>Overtime</h2>
<p>Overtime pay only pays for overtime of actual work hours over 40 hours. In other words, Annual Time cannot be used to be paid for overtime or to "make" 40 hrs. on a time card for the week.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Holiday pay is treated as regular work hours in reference to determining OT pay.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>In the event the company closes for any weather related or any reason outside of IAT control, the day(s) closed will not be compensated with regular pay. You have the option of working on Friday to make up the time or you may use your annual time for compensation. If annual time is used it will not count towards OT.</p>', 35, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Sick Time', 'sick-time', '<h2>Sick Time</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Everything hurts and I''m dying" Parks and Recreation meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Sick Time is the paid time off you get if you''re feeling under the weather or dealing with an injury that keeps you from working. It''s also there for you if you need to see the doctor, dentist, or eye doctor, or if someone in your family needs your care.</p>
<p>It''s not like a free pass to take time off whenever you feel like it. Think of it more as a special privilege that''s there when you really need it, not something to be taken advantage of. If someone starts going overboard with taking sick days or not following the rules, there might be some consequences.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Permanent full-time employees will earn 80 hours per year (1.54 hours per week) for Sick Time to be taken as paid time off.</strong></p></blockquote>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Sick Time Policy Intro video thumbnail — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Extra or temporary employees are not eligible for sick time.</p>
<h3>Sick Time shall be granted to eligible employees for the following reasons:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Personal illness or injury</li>
<li>Illness of an employee''s spouse, parent, child</li>
<li>Medical, dental or optical appointment</li>
<li>After bereavement leave (refer to section 5.6) has been used for the death of an employee''s spouse, mother, father, brother, sister, child, grandparents, grandchild</li>
<li>Aside from the reasons above, Sick Time may be used for Annual Shutdown</li>
</ul>
<p>If you''re feeling under the weather or can''t make it to work for any reason listed above, make sure to give your supervisor a shout. Call them or drop a message before your day starts. And if you''re out for more than a day, keep them in the loop about how you''re doing, unless they tell you not to bother.</p>
<p>If you don''t keep your supervisor updated, you might not get paid sick leave for the time you''re off. If you''re out for more than 3 days, we''ll need a note from your doctor or if you''ve got any doctor''s appointments planned.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>FUN FACT: Sick time carries over.</strong></p>
<p>Don''t worry about not using all your sick hours; they''ll carry over to next year. You can accumulate up to 160 hours. If you find yourself with more than that at the end of the year, we''ll pay out the extra. But remember, if you''ve used up all your sick time, you''ll have to dip into your annual leave.</p></blockquote>
<blockquote><p><em>Just so we''re clear, sick time can''t be swapped for vacation time.</em></p></blockquote>
<p><strong>REMEMBER!</strong> Before you head back to work, make sure you''ve been fever-free for at least 24 hours. Your manager has the final say on approving your sick leave.</p>', 36, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
