INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Confidentiality and Security when Sending Emails', 'email-confidentiality-and-security', '<h2>Confidentiality and Security when Sending Emails</h2>
<p>When we''re talking about handling sensitive info in emails, it''s super important to play it safe and stick to some rules to keep everything under wraps.</p>
<p><strong>Make sure you''re only sending the need-to-know stuff to people who, well, need to know.</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>That means no throwing personal ID numbers, your bank details, or secret business plans into emails unless you''ve got them locked down tight with encryption or some secure way of sending them.</li>
</ul>', 40, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Subject Lines', 'email-subject-lines', '<h2>Email Subject Lines</h2>
<p>When writing subject lines for emails, clarity and descriptiveness are key to ensure recipients understand the purpose and urgency of the message at a glance.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>In a nutshell, just get to the point!</strong></p></blockquote>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Wow, straight to the point" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<ul>
<li>Summarize the main topic or action required in a concise manner.</li>
<li>Avoid vague or ambiguous subject lines that may cause confusion or lead to the email being overlooked.</li>
<li>Consider including relevant keywords to convey the primary focus of the email and compel recipients to open it promptly.</li>
<li>Use specific details or deadlines when applicable to provide context and urgency.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p>By prioritizing clear and descriptive subject lines, senders can enhance the effectiveness of their emails, improve recipient engagement, and streamline communication within the organization.</p></blockquote>', 41, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Structure', 'email-structure', '<h2>Email Structure</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>Effective email structure ensures <strong>clarity, professionalism, and readability.</strong></em></p></blockquote>
<ol>
<li><strong>Begin</strong> with a clear and appropriate greeting or salutation, addressing the recipient by name if possible to personalize the communication.</li>
<li>In the <strong>body</strong> of the email, organize your thoughts logically with proper paragraphing and use bullet points or numbered lists for conveying information concisely, especially for complex topics or action items.</li>
<li>When <strong>closing</strong> the email, include a courteous sign-off such as "Best regards" or "Sincerely," followed by your name and any relevant contact information or job title. Consider adding a professional email signature containing your name, position, company, and contact details to provide recipients with additional context and facilitate further communication.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>Adhering to these best practices for email structure helps ensure that your messages are well-organized, easy to read, and effectively convey the intended message to recipients.</p></blockquote>', 42, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Email Threads', 'email-threads', '<h2>Email Threads</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Email Threads video tutorial — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>When you''re diving into writing emails, stick to what the convo is all about. Veering off into the wild blue yonder can really throw everyone for a loop and muddle up what we''re all trying to get at. Keeping our eyes on the prize, or rather, the topic, helps everyone stay on the same page and chip in their two cents way more effectively.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Not everyone needs to see your reply.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Before you bring everyone into the mix, think about who really needs to be in on the convo. This way, you''re not clogging up inboxes or causing any head-scratching moments.</p>
<p>When managing an email thread, ensure all relevant parties are included to foster great teamwork and cover all perspectives. It''s essential to reply specifically to <strong>only</strong> those who need the information to avoid overwhelming others with unnecessary details.</p>
<p>If someone''s wrapped up a topic with a neat little bow, there''s no need to pile on with a "Thanks for the update" unless it really adds something. <strong>Let''s keep our email chats sharp and concise.</strong></p>
<h3>Email threads:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Don''t go off topic, stay on subject in the thread</li>
<li>Don''t assume "reply all" is necessary.</li>
<li>Consider the involvement of all parties.</li>
<li>Reply to only relevant parties.</li>
<li>Consider not sending pleasantries if the previous email has a conclusive tone.</li>
<li>It''s not always necessary to send something like, "Thanks for the update".</li>
</ul>
<h3>Using "@":</h3>
<ul>
<li>Not acceptable as an introduction.</li>
<li>Not acceptable when addressing a customer; always address customers respectfully.</li>
<li>Only acceptable when highlighting an action item for a team member.</li>
</ul>', 43, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Using @ in Emails', 'email-using-at-sign', '<h2>Using @ in Emails</h2>
<blockquote><p><em>So, about using "@" in our emails, we gotta know when and how to use it correctly.</em></p></blockquote>
<p>Throwing "@" into the mix is perfect when you wanna flag an <strong>action item</strong> for a specific team member. It''s like saying, "Hey, check this out!" or "This one''s on you!" It helps everyone zero in on what they gotta do, making sure nothing slips through the cracks.</p>
<p><strong>BUT</strong>, and it''s a big BUT, rolling into an email with "@" right off the bat? Not the best move.</p>
<p>And when it comes to chatting with customers or the folks outside our little world, let''s keep "@" out of it. We wanna make sure we''re always coming across as the respectful and polished pros we are.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: Email Policy — Using "@" video tutorial — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>', 44, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Timely Responses', 'email-timely-responses', '<h2>Timely Responses</h2>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Still Waiting" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<p>Getting back to emails on time is pretty much the golden rule if you want to keep things running smoothly and make sure everyone''s on the same page.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>The general rule is to respond within a day or two, tops, unless there''s a really good reason you can''t.</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>If for some reason, you can''t dive into a full reply right away, it''s totally OK to just drop a quick note saying, "Got your email! Thanks, and I''ll get back to you soon." It''s like giving a virtual high five, letting them know you''re on it. It keeps the trust tank full and shows you''ve got your act together.</p>
<blockquote><p>And for those times when you''re swamped or out of the office, setting up an auto-reply is a lifesaver.</p></blockquote>
<p>If a message needs more brainpower or time than you''ve got right at that moment, a heads-up to the sender with a "Hey, I need a bit more time but haven''t forgotten you!" can work wonders. It''s all about keeping that conversation flowing and making sure no one''s left hanging.</p>', 45, TRUE, 2
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
WHERE c.slug = 'company' AND m.slug = 'company-policies'
ON CONFLICT (module_id, slug) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO learn_lessons (module_id, title, slug, content, display_order, is_published, estimated_minutes)
SELECT m.id, 'Handling Different Types of Email Inquiries', 'email-handling-different-types', '<h2>Handling Different Types of Email Inquiries</h2>
<p>When you''re juggling all sorts of emails, whether they''re just folks asking questions or needing a bit more from you, it''s super important to keep calm and stay sharp.</p>
<figure class="img-missing"><figcaption>📷 Image from Trainual: "Everybody just chill, just relax" meme — re-upload via admin editor</figcaption></figure>
<h3>Respond to simple inquiries quickly and clearly.</h3>
<p>For complex emails, acknowledge receipt immediately and estimate a response time, involving team members as necessary.</p>
<p>Empathize with customer complaints, apologize if needed, and take action to resolve issues, ensuring satisfaction.</p>
<p>Handle confidential information with care, adhering to company policies.</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>Effective email communication is crucial for maintaining professional relationships and solving problems.</strong></p></blockquote>', 46, TRUE, 3
FROM learn_modules m JOIN learn_categories c ON c.id = m.category_id
